        This method creates an instance of Unknown that, when evaluated, invokes the r(frege.rt.Lazy<T4>, frege.rt.Lazy<T3>, frege.rt.Lazy<T2>, frege.rt.Lazy<T1>) method of this function.

        Use of this method is preferrable if all arguments are known compared to repeated invokation of the single argument form since intermediate closure creation is saved.

      • r

        public abstract Lazy<T5> r(Lazy<T4> arg4,
         Lazy<T3> arg3,
         Lazy<T2> arg2,
         Lazy<T1> arg1)

        Run the function.

        The run method will be called by the Fun3.r(frege.rt.Lazy<T3>, frege.rt.Lazy<T2>, frege.rt.Lazy<T1>) method of the function value resulting from this.a(...). It actually performs computation and returns a result or another lazy value that will evaluate to the result.
        This method must be implemented by all subclasses.

        Note that the arguments must be passed in reverse order. The reason is that in this way the byte code for any intermediate closure will only have to push its argument and invoke the next higher closure's r method. A reordering of the arguments on the stack will not be needed. This could save a substantial amounts of memory writes (I hope).

        Returns:
        boxed and possibly lazy result
